{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2fc92cf8-3af3-4357-bf35-4f7e7b67b3f1","content":"`SafeAreaEdges` isn't a real `ContentPage` property in .NET MAUI — that's likely why it has no effect. You need platform-specific configuration:\n\n**iOS** — disable safe area insets on the page:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\">\n```\n\n**Android** — extend content behind system bars. In your `MainActivity.cs` or platform startup:\n\n```csharp\n#if ANDROID\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\n// In your MainActivity.OnCreate or MauiProgram.cs builder:\nWindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n```\n\nOr in `MauiProgram.cs` using lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnCreate((activity, _) =>\n    {\n        WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(activity.Window!, false);\n    }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Note:** On Android 15+ (API 35), apps are edge-to-edge by default, so you may only need the iOS fix if you're targeting recent devices.\n\nThen your `Image` should use `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"` to actually fill the space:\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b6622b81-e5c8-4461-984d-8e4d3661a634","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making an image go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app, behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but the image still has padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. In .NET MAUI, to achieve true edge-to-edge content, you need to do more than just set `SafeAreaEdges`. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. **Safe area insets** - `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage should help, but this is an iOS concept primarily.\n\n\n2. On iOS, I need to use `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` to tell the platform to ignore safe area constraints, while on Android the approach involves configuring the window to extend into system bar areas. The real issue is that `SafeAreaEdges` alone doesn't fully disable safe area behavior across both platforms.\n\nSetting up the iOS platform-specific configuration... For Android, I need to use platform-specific code like `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(window, false)` or configure the `Window` and `StatusBarStyle` APIs. Since `SafeAreaEdges` isn't actually a property on `ContentPage` in MAUI, the user is likely looking for `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"False\"` on iOS and proper edge-to-edge configuration on Android, which requires a bit more setup depending on the .NET version.","outputTokens":1279,"requestId":"3C26:16C73:DD3AD5:112E3FA:6A012C81"},"id":"8df63e7a-0b78-45f4-9685-2a1291b13967","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:10:52.951Z","parentId":"40efc91b-14c1-4d38-9048-aaec2b416b8b"}
